One meaningful decision per node.

A node that contains two decisions is two nodes. A node that contains none is
not a node, it is a restatement, and it should not exist.

Write each node as a single declarative sentence in the imperative. No bullet
lists inside a node. No prose paragraphs. If you cannot say it in one sentence,
it is not one decision.

Propose only the decisions the parent leaves genuinely open. A name you know -
"insertion sort", "binary search", "reverse a string" - determines its own steps,
and decomposing it yields nodes that describe the code instead of causing it. A
child survives only if it bends the code the parent alone would produce. If the
parent determines everything, return leaf. Zero children is a common and correct
answer.
